cp -r [sourcedir1] [destinationdir2] : copies source to destination
cp -i file1 file2 : copies file1 to file 2, but asks for confirmation before overwriting
cp -v file1 file2 : Copies file1 to file2 and displays the copying process.
moves or renames
mv file1 dir/ - moves file to directory
mv oldname newname : renames the file
mv -i file1 dir/ : confirm before overwriting the file. if y/no
mv -v file1 dir/ : prints a message showing the move operation.
remove
rem file.txt : deletes the file
rm -r folder : deletes directory and all files/subdirectories inside it.
rm -f file : forces the deletion of file
rm -i file : ask for permission before deleting

stat 
gives information about the file's size, permissions, owner, access time, modification time

find
find . -name [file.txt] : search the file by its name and it gives the file path . it will search in its own directory
find /home -type f : searches only files from the starting directory
find . -size +10M : finds the files more than 10mb
find . -mtime -1 : finds the files which are modified within a day
cat
cat f1.txt f2.txt > combined.txt :combines both txt file content to the new file
cat -e file.txt > : print each newline with $
cat -t filename : print content in file and but prints tab as ^
cat -u file name: copy one byte at a time
cat -v filename:  Display nonprinting characters as escape sequences with M-x for high ascii characters (>127), and ^x for other nonprinting chars

less
less filename :lets us scroll through the large file
while scrolling 
space : next page
b : previous page
/[text we want to search in large file]:searches the given text
q : means quitting from the page
less -N filename : shows line numbers for each line in the file
less -S filename :long lines do not continue on the next line and must be viewed by horizontal scrolling.
  Right arrow : to see the hidden part of the hidden part
	left arrow: to go back

more
more filename : view file one screen at a time

head
head filename: show first lines of a file
head -n [Number][filename]: gives the first N number of lines
head -c [bytes][filename]: gives the specific bytes of characters

tail filename :show end lines of a file
tail -n [Number][filename]: gives the last N number of lines
tail -c [bytes][filename]: gives the specific bytes of characters from last

vim filename : it helps to edit the text in the file in mobaxterm
	after entering the editor 
	i : for insert mode
		esc-->:wq--> to save and exit the editor
		q! : exit without saving
		dd: for deleting line
		yy: for copying the line 
		p : for pasting
